{{Infobox book | name = The Nature of Prejudice | title_orig = | translator = | image = | caption = | author = [[Gordon Allport]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = Psychology of prejudice | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Addison-Wesley]] | pub_date = 1954 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print | pages = | isbn = | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Nature of Prejudice''''' is a 1954 book by American psychologist [[Gordon Allport]], considered to be a seminal work in [[social psychology]] on the topic of [[prejudice]].
==Impact and significance== The book was already called a classic a decade after its initial publication, in 1965.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gordon|first=Albert I.|date=1965|title=Review of ''The Nature of Prejudice'' by Gordon W. Allport; ''The Religious Factor'' by Gerhard Lenski; ''Protestant, Catholic, Jew'' by Will Herberg; ''Religious Conflict in America'' by Earl Raab; ''American Race Relations Today'' by Earl Raab|journal=American Jewish Historical Quarterly|volume=55|issue=1|pages=107–109|jstor=23873648}}</ref> Irwin Katz, writing in ''[[Political Psychology]]'' in 1991 on the topic of "classics in political psychology", called the book a landmark and "one of the most influential and often-cited publications in the entire field of [[intergroup relations]]".<ref name=":0" /> In 2016 Thomas F. Pettigrew and Kerstin Hammann described the book as "probably the most read volume in the history of social psychology", noting that it has received numerous translations and remains influential in the modern study of prejudice.<ref name=":1">Pettigrew, T. F., & Hammann, K. Gordon Willard. 2016. [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Thomas_Pettigrew/publication/303366079_English_translation_of_Pettigrew_T_F_Hammann_K_Gordon_Willard_Allport_The_nature_of_prejudice_In_S_Salzborn_Ed_Klassiker_der_Sozialwissenshaften_Classics_of_social_science_Pp_174-178_Wiesbaden_Germany/links/573e63b908aea45ee842ec36/English-translation-of-Pettigrew-T-F-Hammann-K-Gordon-Willard-Allport-The-nature-of-prejudice-In-S-Salzborn-Ed-Klassiker-der-Sozialwissenshaften-Classics-of-social-science-Pp-174-178-Wiesbaden Allport: The nature of prejudice.] In S. Salzborn (Ed.), Klassiker der Sozialwissenshaften [Classics of social science]. Pp. 174-178. Wiesbaden, Germany: Springer. [English version].</ref> In a volume published roughly on the fiftieth anniversary of the book's original debut, ''On the Nature of Prejudice: Fifty Years after Allport'' (2008), the authors referred to Allport's book as "the fundamental work for social psychology of prejudice" and the most widely cited work on the subject, still used in teaching and quoted in modern research.<ref name="DovidioGlick2008">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CDSyHPt98E0|title=On the Nature of Prejudice: Fifty Years after Allport|author1=John F. Dovidio|author2=Peter Glick|author3=Laurie A. Rudman|date=15 April 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4051-5192-4|page=1}}</ref>
Describing the book's significance, Katz noted that it "defined the field of intergroup relations for social psychologist as the study of prejudice and its effects on group interactions".<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Katz|first=Irwin|date=1991|title=Gordon Allport's "The Nature of Prejudice"|journal=Political Psychology|volume=12|issue=1|pages=125–157|doi=10.2307/3791349|jstor=3791349}}</ref> He noted, however, that Allport's assumption that prejudice causes discrimination has still to be proven beyond doubt;<ref name=":0" /> though other scholars also stressed that many of other assumptions Allport expressed in the book have become accepted since its publication.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dovidio|first=John F.|date=2001|title=On the Nature of Contemporary Prejudice: The Third Wave|journal=Journal of Social Issues|language=en|volume=57|issue=4|pages=829–849|doi=10.1111/0022-4537.00244|issn=0022-4537}}</ref> Pettigrew and Hammann selected, as the book's most lasting contribution, its success in redefining the relation between intergroup contact and prejudice: while previously some scholars argued that contact between different groups leads to increased prejudice and conflict, Allport argued to the contrary, a view that Pettigrew and Hammann describe as supported by "literally hundreds of studies from dozens of nations".<ref name=":1" /> Another major influence of the book was the later formulation of the [[common ingroup identity]] theory.<ref name=":1" /> Pettigrew and Hammann also credit Allport's ideas with influencing government policies, in the [[United States]] and elsewhere, which have successfully reduced levels of prejudice.<ref name=":1" />
Another idea introduced in the book became known as [[Allport's Scale]], a measure of prejudice starting from [[antilocution]] and ending up at [[Genocide|genocidal extermination]]. In simpler terms, Allport argued that even simple prejudice, if left unchecked, can develop into an extreme form.<ref name="BrynSteve2017">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CvPBDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA203|title=Leading Policing in Europe: An Empirical Study of Strategic Police Leadership|author1=Caless, Bryn|author2=Tong, Steve|date=18 January 2017|publisher=Policy Press|isbn=978-1-4473-1574-2|page=203}}</ref>
In addition to being highly influential in the field of social psychology, the revised (and shortened) second edition of the book (''The Nature of Prejudice: Abridged'') published in 1958 was also a success on the mass market, being written in a relatively simple way that was accessible to a general readership.<ref name=":1" /> One of the reasons for its success, in Pettigrew and Hammann's opinion, was the boldness of its topic: while targeting a [[White Anglo-Saxon Protestant|white, Protestant, American]], and mostly male readership, it discussed numerous examples of anti-African-American, anti-Jewish, anti-Catholic, and anti-female prejudices.<ref name=":1" />
